ctory. This requires real filesystem operations (remove, recreate directories) combined with monitoring the daemon's subprocess state. A Unit test with mocked fs.watch wouldn't test whether the daemon's error handling and rewatch logic actually works under real OS filesystem disruptions.","test_description":"Start the daemon watching a real temporary directory. While running, remove the directory completely. Verify the daemon either gracefully handles the error or detects it. Recreate the directory. Verify the daemon resumes watching it without requiring a restart, and new files in the recreated directory are processed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"System level is required because the failure involves both OS filesystem state changes and daemon subprocess behavior under real disruption.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.1}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure mode is that files are processed in arrival order rather than creation-timestamp order, implying the code fails to read or sort by file timestamps. Testing requires real files with real creation timestamps from the filesystem. A Unit test with mocked fs.stat could hide a failure where the code doesn't actually call fs.stat or sorts incorrectly. Real files with staggered creation times ensure the timestamp-reading and sorting logic is correct.","test_description":"Create multiple temporary files with distinct creation times (e.g., file1 created at T, file2 at T+100ms, file3 at T+50ms). Trigger a batch of filesystem events for all files simultaneously. Verify they are processed in order file1 → file3 → file2, i.e., sorted by creation timestamp, not arrival order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration level is appropriate because the test needs real file timestamps but not OS-specific behaviors like event sequences or subprocess management.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure mode is that the daemon processes a partially-written file, corrupting the transformation output or reading incomplete data. Detecting 'still being written' depends on OS-specific mechanisms: file locks, inode state, file size changes, or handle status. A Unit test with mocked file state cannot reliably capture how the real OS indicates a file is in-progress. Real file I/O with open handles is required.","test_description":"Open a real temporary file for writing (leaving the handle open). Fire a file-arrival event while the write is in progress. Verify the daemon does not pick it up for processing. Close the file. Verify the daemon then detects and processes it. Repeat with different write patterns (small vs. large, buffered vs. unbuffered) to ensure robustness.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"System level is required because detecting write-in-progress is an OS-level concern; mocking file state would miss real failure modes.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0.05}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13481,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13481},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"486d58b8-89c9-40d9-b613-2e1618e17349","uuid":"3c1ec030-8487-462a-956e-42e46e49f97c"}
